    </header>
    <para styleclass="Normal" style="margin-top:19px; margin-bottom:14px; line-height:1.0; tabstops:none;"><var styleclass="Normal" style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9pt; vertical-align:baseline; color:#000000;">&lt;%PROGNAME%&gt;</var><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9pt; vertical-align:baseline; color:#000000;" translate="true"> makes a clear conceptual distinction between models, views and diagrams. A </text><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold; vertical-align:baseline; color:#000000;" translate="true">Model</text><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9pt; vertical-align:baseline; color:#000000;" translate="true"> is an element that contains information for a software model. A </text><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold; vertical-align:baseline; color:#000000;" translate="true">View</text><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9pt; vertical-align:baseline; color:#000000;" translate="true"> is a visual expression of the information contained in a model, and a </text><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9pt; font-weight:bold; vertical-align:baseline; color:#000000;" translate="true">Diagram </text><text styleclass="Normal" style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:9pt; vertical-align:baseline; color:#000000;" translate="true">is a collection of view elements that represent the user’s specific design thoughts.</text></para>
